   <refbody>
      <section class="- topic/section ">
         <indexterm class="- topic/indexterm ">external connection board</indexterm>
         <p class="- topic/p ">The external
connection board contains terminals and connectors for external connections
to and from the UPS. Terminals are mounted for connection to:<ul class="- topic/ul ">
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">various signalling switches</p>
               </li>
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">ON/OFF buttons</p>
               </li>
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">emergency stop (may be supplied from an external source)</p>
               </li>
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">a temperature sensor</p>
               </li>
            </ul>
         </p>
         <p class="- topic/p ">
            <hazardstatement type="notice" class="+ topic/note hazard-d/hazardstatement ">
               <messagepanel class="+ topic/ul hazard-d/messagepanel ">
                  <typeofhazard class="+ topic/li hazard-d/typeofhazard "/>
                  <howtoavoid class="+ topic/li hazard-d/howtoavoid ">
                     <sl class="- topic/sl ">
                        <sli class="- topic/sli ">The input contacts on the external connection board are designed
for internal use only. The wires connected to these terminals must
not be lead out of the UPS cabinet. No external supply voltage is
allowed.</sli>
                     </sl>
                     <sl class="- topic/sl ">
                        <sli class="- topic/sli ">Do not interchange wires of different functions (battery temperature
sensors, REPO, input contacts and output relays) as this will damage
the board.</sli>
                     </sl>
                  </howtoavoid>
               </messagepanel>
            </hazardstatement>
         </p>
         <fig class="- topic/fig ">
            <title class="- topic/title ">Board layout</title>
            <image href="../Images/0p2553a_pcb_external_connection_board_w120mm_0000104040.svg"
                   placement="inline"
                   class="- topic/image "/>
         </fig>
      </section>
      <section class="- topic/section ">
         <title class="- topic/title ">Input Contacts and Output Relays</title>
         <p class="- topic/p ">Summary
of signals:<ul class="- topic/ul ">
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">1 common alarm output relays</p>
               </li>
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">2 free programmable output relays</p>
               </li>
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">1 REPO input contact</p>
               </li>
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">2 free programmable inputs contacts</p>
               </li>
               <li class="- topic/li ">
                  <p class="- topic/p ">1 battery temperature input and/or ambient temperature (free
programmable)</p>
               </li>
            </ul>
         </p>
      </section>
      <section class="- topic/section ">
         <title class="- topic/title ">Assignment</title>
         <p class="- topic/p ">All of the input contacts and
output relays can be assigned to functions and alarms by configuration
(no fixed assignments). The Remote Emergency Power OFF (REPO) is an
exception as it is always assigned as shown in the connection diagram
for the external connection board. There are two connection options:</p>
